# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dna-sequencing-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The Sanger method is used to amplify a target segment of DNA, so that the DNA sequence can be determined precisely.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The incorporation of ddNTPs in the reaction valves are simply used to terminate the synthesis of a growing DNA strand, resulting in partially replicated DNA fragments.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] This is because DNA polymerase requires the 3' OH group of the growing chain and the 5' phosphate group of the incoming dNTP to create a phosphodiester bond.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] Sometimes the DNA polymerase will incorporate a ddNTP and the absence of the 3' OH group will interrupt the condensation reaction between the 5' phosphate (following the cleavage of pyrophosphate) of the incoming nucleotide with the 3' hydroxyl group of the previous nucleotide on the growing strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] This condensation reaction would normally occur with the incorporation of a non-modified dNTP by DNA polymerase.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] In the simplest of terms, the nucleophilic attack of the 3' OH group leads to the addition of a nucleotide onto a growing chain.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The absence of the 3' hydroxyl group inhibits this nucleophilic attack from happening, disabling the DNA polymerase's ability to continue with its function.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] This discovery led to its appropriate name "Chain-terminating nucleotides".
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The dideoxyribonucleotides do not have a 3' hydroxyl group, hence no further chain elongation can occur once this dideoxynucleotide is on the chain.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] This can lead to the termination of the DNA sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] Thus, these molecules form the basis of the dideoxy chain-termination method of DNA sequencing, which was reported by Frederick Sanger and his team in 1977 as an extension of earlier work.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] Dideoxynucleotides are useful in the sequencing of DNA in combination with electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] A DNA sample that undergoes PCR (polymerase chain reaction) in a mixture containing all four deoxynucleotides and one dideoxynucleotide will produce strands of length equal to the position of each base of the type that complements the type having a dideoxynucleotide present.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] That the taq polymerase used in PCR favors the ddGTP, is a pattern observed in various research.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] That is, each nucleotide base of that particular type has a probability of being bonded to not a deoxynucleotide but rather a dideoxynucleotide, which ends chain elongation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] Therefore, if the sample then undergoes electrophoresis, there will be a band present for each length at which the complement of the dideoxynucleotide is present.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] It is now common to use fluorescent dideoxynucleotides such that each one of the four has a different fluorescence that can be detected by a sequencer; thus only one reaction is needed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] In a patented method, Tetrahydrofuran was used in a solvent containing 50 g (0.205 mols) of uridine (or, presumably, any unprotected nucleoside), 112 ml (1.03 mols) of methyl orthoformate and 10 g (52.6 mmols) of *para*-toluenesulfonic acid at room temperature with stirring.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] After stirring at room temperature for 24 hours, the reaction mixture was poured into an aqueous sodium bicarbonate solution followed by extraction with chloroform 5 times.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The extract was dried over sodium sulfate and concentrated to give 49.5 g (0.173 mols) of 2',3'-o-methoxymethylideneuridine (yield, 84.5%).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] After this reaction, the uridine example product 2',3'-o-methoxymethylideneuridine is then dissolved in 50 ml of acetic anhydride at room temperature with stirring.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The solution was heated to 140 °C. and kept at this temperature for 5 hours under reflux of the solvent.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] After cooling to room temperature, the solvent was removed by distillation under reduced pressure, 50 ml of water were added, and the mixture was extracted 3 times with 100 ml of chloroform.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The extract was concentrated under reduced pressure, 30% ammonia water to obtain an 82.3% yield of 2',3'-dideoxy-2',3'-didehydrouridine.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] This product example is then hydrated to remove the double bond through dissolving it in methanol (10 ml) containing a catalyst (wet 5% palladium on carbon) (400 mg) in an atmosphere of hydrogen for 1 h to obtain the resultant dideoxynucleoside ( 2',3'-dideoxyuridine in this case).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] The dye nucleo*tide* to be used will likely occur by treatment with a phosphorylation enzyme and biotinylation and reaction of the biotinylated substance with the dye.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dideoxynucleotide] It is possible that immediate reaction with the dye may also occur, but extending the arm is claimed to increase efficiency in the case of using a mutant form of DNA polymerase.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Knowledge of **DNA sequences** has become indispensable for basic biological research, DNA Genographic Projects and in numerous applied fields such as medical diagnosis, biotechnology, forensic biology, virology and biological systematics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Comparing healthy and mutated DNA sequences can diagnose different diseases including various cancers, characterize antibody repertoire, and can be used to guide patient treatment.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Having a quick way to sequence DNA allows for faster and more individualized medical care to be administered, and for more organisms to be identified and cataloged.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The rapid advancements in DNA sequencing technology have played a crucial role in sequencing complete genomes of humans, as well as numerous animal, plant, and microbial species.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The first DNA sequences were obtained in the early 1970s by academic researchers using laborious methods based on two-dimensional chromatography.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Following the development of fluorescence-based sequencing methods with a DNA sequencer, DNA sequencing has become easier and orders of magnitude faster.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing can be used to determine the sequence of individual genes, larger genetic regions (i.e. clusters of genes or operons), full chromosomes, or entire genomes of any organism.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing is also the most efficient way to indirectly sequence RNA or proteins (via their open reading frames).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In fact, DNA sequencing has become a key technology in many areas of biology and other sciences such as medicine, forensics, and anthropology.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Sequencing is used in molecular biology to study genomes and the proteins they encode.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Information obtained using sequencing allows researchers to identify changes in genes and noncoding DNA (including regulatory sequences), associations with diseases and phenotypes, and identify potential drug targets.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Since DNA is an informative macromolecule in terms of transmission from one generation to another, DNA sequencing is used in evolutionary biology to study how different organisms are related and how they evolved.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In February 2021, scientists reported, for the first time, the sequencing of DNA from animal remains, a mammoth in this instance, over a million years old, the oldest DNA sequenced to date.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The field of metagenomics involves identification of organisms present in a body of water, sewage, dirt, debris filtered from the air, or swab samples from organisms.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Knowing which organisms are present in a particular environment is critical to research in ecology, epidemiology, microbiology, and other fields.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Sequencing enables researchers to determine which types of microbes may be present in a microbiome, for example.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] As most viruses are too small to be seen by a light microscope, sequencing is one of the main tools in virology to identify and study the virus.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Viral genomes can be based in DNA or RNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] RNA viruses are more time-sensitive for genome sequencing, as they degrade faster in clinical samples.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Traditional Sanger sequencing and next-generation sequencing are used to sequence viruses in basic and clinical research, as well as for the diagnosis of emerging viral infections, molecular epidemiology of viral pathogens, and drug-resistance testing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] There are more than 2.3 million unique viral sequences in GenBank.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2019, NGS has surpassed traditional Sanger as the most popular approach for generating viral genomes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] During the 1997 avian influenza outbreak, viral sequencing determined that the influenza sub-type originated through reassortment between quail and poultry.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This led to legislation in Hong Kong that prohibited selling live quail and poultry together at market.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Viral sequencing can also be used to estimate when a viral outbreak began by using a molecular clock technique.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Medical technicians may sequence genes (or, theoretically, full genomes) from patients to determine if there is risk of genetic diseases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This is a form of genetic testing, though not all genetic tests involve complete genome DNA sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] As of 2013 DNA sequencing was increasingly used to diagnose and treat rare diseases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] As more and more genes are identified that cause rare genetic diseases, molecular diagnoses for patients become more mainstream.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing allows clinicians to identify genetic diseases, improve disease management, provide reproductive counseling, and more effective therapies.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Gene sequencing panels are used to identify multiple potential genetic causes of a suspected disorder.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Also, DNA sequencing may be useful for determining a specific bacteria, to allow for more precise antibiotics treatments, hereby reducing the risk of creating antimicrobial resistance in bacteria populations.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing may be used along with DNA profiling methods for forensic identification and paternity testing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA testing has evolved tremendously in the last few decades to ultimately link a DNA print to what is under investigation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA patterns in fingerprint, saliva, hair follicles, etc. uniquely separate each living organism from another.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Testing DNA is a technique which can detect specific genomes in a DNA strand to produce a unique and individualized pattern.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The canonical structure of DNA has four bases: thymine (T), adenine (A), cytosine (C), and guanine (G).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing is the determination of the physical order of these bases in a molecule of DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However, there are many other bases that may be present in a molecule.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In some viruses (specifically, bacteriophage), cytosine may be replaced by hydroxymethyl- or hydroxymethylglucose- cytosine.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In mammalian DNA, variant bases with methyl groups or phosphosulfate may be found.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Depending on the sequencing technique, a particular modification, e.g., the 5mC (5-Methylcytosine) common in humans, may or may not be detected.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In almost all organisms, DNA is synthesized in vivo using only the 4 canonical bases; modification that occurs post replication creates other bases like 5 methyl C.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However, some bacteriophage can incorporate a non standard base directly.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In addition to modifications, DNA is under constant assault by environmental agents such as UV and Oxygen radicals.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] At the present time, the presence of such damaged bases is not detected by most DNA sequencing methods, although PacBio has published on this.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) was first discovered and isolated by Friedrich Miescher in 1869, but it remained under-studied for many decades because proteins, rather than DNA, were thought to hold the genetic blueprint to life.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This situation changed after 1944 as a result of some experiments by Oswald Avery, Colin MacLeod, and Maclyn McCarty demonstrating that purified DNA could change one strain of bacteria into another.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This was the first time that DNA was shown capable of transforming the properties of cells.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1953, James Watson and Francis Crick put forward their double-helix model of DNA, based on crystallized X-ray structures being studied by Rosalind Franklin.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] According to the model, DNA is composed of two strands of nucleotides coiled around each other, linked together by hydrogen bonds and running in opposite directions.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Each strand is composed of four complementary nucleotides – adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G) and thymine (T) – with an A on one strand always paired with T on the other, and C always paired with G.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] They proposed that such a structure allowed each strand to be used to reconstruct the other, an idea central to the passing on of hereditary information between generations.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The foundation for sequencing proteins was first laid by the work of Frederick Sanger who by 1955 had completed the sequence of all the amino acids in insulin, a small protein secreted by the pancreas.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This provided the first conclusive evidence that proteins were chemical entities with a specific molecular pattern rather than a random mixture of material suspended in fluid.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Sanger's success in sequencing insulin spurred on x-ray crystallographers, including Watson and Crick, who by now were trying to understand how DNA directed the formation of proteins within a cell.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Soon after attending a series of lectures given by Frederick Sanger in October 1954, Crick began developing a theory which argued that the arrangement of nucleotides in DNA determined the sequence of amino acids in proteins, which in turn helped determine the function of a protein.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] RNA sequencing was one of the earliest forms of nucleotide sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The major landmark of RNA sequencing is the sequence of the first complete gene and the complete genome of Bacteriophage MS2, identified and published by Walter Fiers and his coworkers at the University of Ghent (Ghent, Belgium), in 1972 and 1976.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Traditional RNA sequencing methods require the creation of a cDNA molecule which must be sequenced.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The first method for determining DNA sequences involved a location-specific primer extension strategy established by Ray Wu, a geneticist, at Cornell University in 1970.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA polymerase catalysis and specific nucleotide labeling, both of which figure prominently in current sequencing schemes, were used to sequence the cohesive ends of lambda phage DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Between 1970 and 1973, Wu, scientist Radha Padmanabhan and colleagues demonstrated that this method can be employed to determine any DNA sequence using synthetic location-specific primers.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Walter Gilbert, a biochemist, and Allan Maxam, a molecular geneticist, at Harvard also developed sequencing methods, including one for "DNA sequencing by chemical degradation".
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1973, Gilbert and Maxam reported the sequence of 24 basepairs using a method known as wandering-spot analysis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Advancements in sequencing were aided by the concurrent development of recombinant DNA technology, allowing DNA samples to be isolated from sources other than viruses.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Two years later in 1975, Frederick Sanger, a biochemist, and Alan Coulson, a genome scientist, developed a method to sequence DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The technique known as the "Plus and Minus" method, involved supplying all the components of the DNA but excluding the reaction of one of the four bases needed to complete the DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1976, Gilbert and Maxam, invented a method for rapidly sequencing DNA while at Harvard, known as the Maxam–Gilbert sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The technique involved treating radiolabelled DNA with a chemical and using a polyacrylamide gel to determine the sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1977, Sanger then adopted a primer-extension strategy to develop more rapid DNA sequencing methods at the MRC Centre, Cambridge, UK.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This technique was similar to his "Plus and Minus" strategy, however, it was based upon the selective incorporation of chain-terminating dideoxynucleotides (ddNTPs) by DNA polymerase during in vitro DNA replication.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Sanger published this method in the same year.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The first full DNA genome to be sequenced was that of bacteriophage φX174 in 1977.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Medical Research Council scientists deciphered the complete DNA sequence of the Epstein-Barr virus in 1984, finding it contained 172,282 nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Completion of the sequence marked a significant turning point in DNA sequencing because it was achieved with no prior genetic profile knowledge of the virus.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] A non-radioactive method for transferring the DNA molecules of sequencing reaction mixtures onto an immobilizing matrix during electrophoresis was developed by Herbert Pohl and co-workers in the early 1980s.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Followed by the commercialization of the DNA sequencer "Direct-Blotting-Electrophoresis-System GATC 1500" by GATC Biotech, which was intensively used in the framework of the EU genome-sequencing programme, the complete DNA sequence of the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* chromosome II.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Hood's laboratory at the California Institute of Technology announced the first semi-automated DNA sequencing machine in 1986.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This was followed by Applied Biosystems' marketing of the first fully automated sequencing machine, the ABI 370, in 1987 and by Dupont's Genesis 2000 which used a novel fluorescent labeling technique enabling all four dideoxynucleotides to be identified in a single lane.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] National Institutes of Health (NIH) had begun large-scale sequencing trials on *Mycoplasma capricolum*, *Escherichia coli*, *Caenorhabditis elegans*, and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* at a cost of US$0.75 per base.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Meanwhile, sequencing of human cDNA sequences called expressed sequence tags began in Craig Venter's lab, an attempt to capture the coding fraction of the human genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1995, Venter, Hamilton Smith, and colleagues at The Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) published the first complete genome of a free-living organism, the bacterium *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The circular chromosome contains 1,830,137 bases and its publication in the journal Science marked the first published use of whole-genome shotgun sequencing, eliminating the need for initial mapping efforts.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] By 2003, the Human Genome Project's shotgun sequencing methods had been used to produce a draft sequence of the human genome; it had a 92% accuracy.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2022, scientists successfully sequenced the last 8% of the human genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The fully sequenced standard reference gene is called GRCh38.p14, and it contains 3.1 billion base pairs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Several new methods for DNA sequencing were developed in the mid to late 1990s and were implemented in commercial DNA sequencers by 2000.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Together these were called the "next-generation" or "second-generation" sequencing (NGS) methods, in order to distinguish them from the earlier methods, including Sanger sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In contrast to the first generation of sequencing, NGS technology is typically characterized by being highly scalable, allowing the entire genome to be sequenced at once.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Usually, this is accomplished by fragmenting the genome into small pieces, randomly sampling for a fragment, and sequencing it using one of a variety of technologies, such as those described below.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] An entire genome is possible because multiple fragments are sequenced at once (giving it the name "massively parallel" sequencing) in an automated process.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] NGS technology has tremendously empowered researchers to look for insights into health, anthropologists to investigate human origins, and is catalyzing the "Personalized Medicine" movement.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However, it has also opened the door to more room for error.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] There are many software tools to carry out the computational analysis of NGS data, often compiled at online platforms such as CSI NGS Portal, each with its own algorithm.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Even the parameters within one software package can change the outcome of the analysis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In addition, the large quantities of data produced by DNA sequencing have also required development of new methods and programs for sequence analysis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Several efforts to develop standards in the NGS field have been attempted to address these challenges, most of which have been small-scale efforts arising from individual labs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Most recently, a large, organized, FDA-funded effort has culminated in the BioCompute standard.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] On 26 October 1990, Roger Tsien, Pepi Ross, Margaret Fahnestock and Allan J Johnston filed a patent describing stepwise ("base-by-base") sequencing with removable 3' blockers on DNA arrays (blots and single DNA molecules).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1996, Pål Nyrén and his student Mostafa Ronaghi at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm published their method of pyrosequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] On 1 April 1997, Pascal Mayer and Laurent Farinelli submitted patents describing DNA colony sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA sample preparation and random surface-polymerase chain reaction (PCR) arraying methods described in this patent, coupled to Roger Tsien et al.'s "base-by-base" sequencing method, is now implemented in Illumina's Hi-Seq genome sequencers.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1998, Phil Green and Brent Ewing of the University of Washington described their phred quality score for sequencer data analysis, a landmark analysis technique that gained widespread adoption, and which is still the most common metric for assessing the accuracy of a sequencing platform.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Lynx Therapeutics published and marketed massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS), in 2000.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method incorporated a parallelized, adapter/ligation-mediated, bead-based sequencing technology and served as the first commercially available "next-generation" sequencing method, though no DNA sequencers were sold to independent laboratories.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Allan Maxam and Walter Gilbert published a DNA sequencing method in 1977 based on chemical modification of DNA and subsequent cleavage at specific bases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Also known as chemical sequencing, this method allowed purified samples of double-stranded DNA to be used without further cloning.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method's use of radioactive labeling and its technical complexity discouraged extensive use after refinements in the Sanger methods had been made.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Maxam-Gilbert sequencing requires radioactive labeling at one 5' end of the DNA and purification of the DNA fragment to be sequenced.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Chemical treatment then generates breaks at a small proportion of one or two of the four nucleotide bases in each of four reactions (G, A+G, C, C+T).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The concentration of the modifying chemicals is controlled to introduce on average one modification per DNA molecule.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Thus a series of labeled fragments is generated, from the radiolabeled end to the first "cut" site in each molecule.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The fragments in the four reactions are electrophoresed side by side in denaturing acrylamide gels for size separation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] To visualize the fragments, the gel is exposed to X-ray film for autoradiography, yielding a series of dark bands each corresponding to a radiolabeled DNA fragment, from which the sequence may be inferred.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method is mostly obsolete as of 2023.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The chain-termination method developed by Frederick Sanger and coworkers in 1977 soon became the method of choice, owing to its relative ease and reliability.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] When invented, the chain-terminator method used fewer toxic chemicals and lower amounts of radioactivity than the Maxam and Gilbert method.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Because of its comparative ease, the Sanger method was soon automated and was the method used in the first generation of DNA sequencers.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Sanger sequencing is the method which prevailed from the 1980s until the mid-2000s.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Over that period, great advances were made in the technique, such as fluorescent labelling, capillary electrophoresis, and general automation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] These developments allowed much more efficient sequencing, leading to lower costs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The Sanger method, in mass production form, is the technology which produced the first human genome in 2001, ushering in the age of genomics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However, later in the decade, radically different approaches reached the market, bringing the cost per genome down from $100 million in 2001 to $10,000 in 2011.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The objective for sequential sequencing by synthesis (SBS) is to determine the sequencing of a DNA sample by detecting the incorporation of a nucleotide by a DNA polymerase.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] An engineered polymerase is used to synthesize a copy of a single strand of DNA and the incorporation of each nucleotide is monitored.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The principle of real-time sequencing by synthesis was first described in 1993 with improvements published some years later.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This principle of real-time sequencing-by-synthesis has been used for almost all massive parallel sequencing instruments, including 454, PacBio, IonTorrent, Illumina and MGI.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] On February 2025, Roche announced development of a new, proprietary sequencing method relying on small molecules.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method "encode[s] the sequence of a target nucleic acid molecule (DNA or RNA) into a measurable surrogate polymer called an Xpandomer", and combined amplification with later detected by a nanopore platform with a CMOS camera.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Large-scale sequencing often aims at sequencing very long DNA pieces, such as whole chromosomes, although large-scale sequencing can also be used to generate very large numbers of short sequences, such as found in phage display.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] For longer targets such as chromosomes, common approaches consist of cutting (with restriction enzymes) or shearing (with mechanical forces) large DNA fragments into shorter DNA fragments.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The fragmented DNA may then be cloned into a DNA vector and amplified in a bacterial host such as *Escherichia coli*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Short DNA fragments purified from individual bacterial colonies are individually sequenced and assembled electronically into one long, contiguous sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Studies have shown that adding a size selection step to collect DNA fragments of uniform size can improve sequencing efficiency and accuracy of the genome assembly.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In these studies, automated sizing has proven to be more reproducible and precise than manual gel sizing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The term "*de novo* sequencing" specifically refers to methods used to determine the sequence of DNA with no previously known sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] *De novo* translates from Latin as "from the beginning".
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Gaps in the assembled sequence may be filled by primer walking.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The different strategies have different tradeoffs in speed and accuracy; shotgun methods are often used for sequencing large genomes, but its assembly is complex and difficult, particularly with sequence repeats often causing gaps in genome assembly.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Most sequencing approaches use an *in vitro* cloning step to amplify individual DNA molecules, because their molecular detection methods are not sensitive enough for single molecule sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Emulsion PCR isolates individual DNA molecules along with primer-coated beads in aqueous droplets within an oil phase.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] A polymerase chain reaction (PCR) then coats each bead with clonal copies of the DNA molecule followed by immobilization for later sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Emulsion PCR is used in the methods developed by Marguilis et al.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] (commercialized by 454 Life Sciences), Shendure and Porreca et al.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] (also known as "polony sequencing") and SOLiD sequencing, (developed by Agencourt, later Applied Biosystems, now Life Technologies).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Emulsion PCR is also used in the GemCode and Chromium platforms developed by 10x Genomics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Shotgun sequencing is a sequencing method designed for analysis of DNA sequences longer than 1000 base pairs, up to and including entire chromosomes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method requires the target DNA to be broken into random fragments.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] After sequencing individual fragments using the chain termination method, the sequences can be reassembled on the basis of their overlapping regions.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method was heavily used in the Human Genome Project.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The high demand for low-cost sequencing has driven the development of high-throughput sequencing technologies that parallelize the sequencing process, producing thousands or millions of sequences concurrently.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] High-throughput sequencing technologies are intended to lower the cost of DNA sequencing beyond what is possible with standard dye-terminator methods.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In ultra-high-throughput sequencing as many as 500,000 sequencing-by-synthesis operations may be run in parallel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Such technologies led to the ability to sequence an entire human genome in as little as one day.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] As of 2019, corporate leaders in the development of high-throughput sequencing products included Illumina, Qiagen and ThermoFisher Scientific.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] SMRT sequencing is based on the sequencing by synthesis approach.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA is synthesized in zero-mode wave-guides (ZMWs) – small well-like containers with the capturing tools located at the bottom of the well.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The sequencing is performed with use of unmodified polymerase (attached to the ZMW bottom) and fluorescently labelled nucleotides flowing freely in the solution.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The wells are constructed in a way that only the fluorescence occurring by the bottom of the well is detected.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The fluorescent label is detached from the nucleotide upon its incorporation into the DNA strand, leaving an unmodified DNA strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] According to Pacific Biosciences (PacBio), the SMRT technology developer, this methodology allows detection of nucleotide modifications (such as cytosine methylation).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This happens through the observation of polymerase kinetics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This approach allows reads of 20,000 nucleotides or more, with average read lengths of 5 kilobases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2015, Pacific Biosciences announced the launch of a new sequencing instrument called the Sequel System, with 1 million ZMWs compared to 150,000 ZMWs in the PacBio RS II instrument.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] SMRT sequencing is referred to as "third-generation" or "long-read" sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA passing through the nanopore changes its ion current.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This change is dependent on the shape, size and length of the DNA sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Each type of the nucleotide blocks the ion flow through the pore for a different period of time.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The method does not require modified nucleotides and is performed in real time.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Nanopore sequencing is referred to as "third-generation" or "long-read" sequencing, along with SMRT sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Early industrial research into this method was based on a technique called 'exonuclease sequencing', where the readout of electrical signals occurred as nucleotides passed by alpha(α)-hemolysin pores covalently bound with cyclodextrin.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However the subsequent commercial method, 'strand sequencing', sequenced DNA bases in an intact strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Two main areas of nanopore sequencing in development are solid state nanopore sequencing, and protein based nanopore sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Protein nanopore sequencing utilizes membrane protein complexes such as α-hemolysin, MspA (*Mycobacterium smegmatis* Porin A) or CssG, which show great promise given their ability to distinguish between individual and groups of nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In contrast, solid-state nanopore sequencing utilizes synthetic materials such as silicon nitride and aluminum oxide and it is preferred for its superior mechanical ability and thermal and chemical stability.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The fabrication method is essential for this type of sequencing given that the nanopore array can contain hundreds of pores with diameters smaller than eight nanometers.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The pore contains a detection region capable of recognizing different bases, with each base generating various time specific signals corresponding to the sequence of bases as they cross the pore which are then evaluated.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Precise control over the DNA transport through the pore is crucial for success.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Various enzymes such as exonucleases and polymerases have been used to moderate this process by positioning them near the pore's entrance.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The first of the high-throughput sequencing technologies, massively parallel signature sequencing (or MPSS, also called next generation sequencing), was developed in the 1990s at Lynx Therapeutics, a company founded in 1992 by Sydney Brenner and Sam Eletr.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] MPSS was a bead-based method that used a complex approach of adapter ligation followed by adapter decoding, reading the sequence in increments of four nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method made it susceptible to sequence-specific bias or loss of specific sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Because the technology was so complex, MPSS was only performed 'in-house' by Lynx Therapeutics and no DNA sequencing machines were sold to independent laboratories.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Lynx Therapeutics merged with Solexa (later acquired by Illumina) in 2004, leading to the development of sequencing-by-synthesis, a simpler approach acquired from Manteia Predictive Medicine, which rendered MPSS obsolete.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However, the essential properties of the MPSS output were typical of later high-throughput data types, including hundreds of thousands of short DNA sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In the case of MPSS, these were typically used for sequencing cDNA for measurements of gene expression levels.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The polony sequencing method, developed in the laboratory of George M.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Church at Harvard, was among the first high-throughput sequencing systems and was used to sequence a full *E. coli* genome in 2005.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] It combined an in vitro paired-tag library with emulsion PCR, an automated microscope, and ligation-based sequencing chemistry to sequence an *E. coli* genome at an accuracy of >99.9999% and a cost approximately 1/9 that of Sanger sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The technology was licensed to Agencourt Biosciences, subsequently spun out into Agencourt Personal Genomics, and eventually incorporated into the Applied Biosystems SOLiD platform.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Applied Biosystems was later acquired by Life Technologies, now part of Thermo Fisher Scientific.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] A parallelized version of pyrosequencing was developed by 454 Life Sciences, which has since been acquired by Roche Diagnostics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The method amplifies DNA inside water droplets in an oil solution (emulsion PCR), with each droplet containing a single DNA template attached to a single primer-coated bead that then forms a clonal colony.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The sequencing machine contains many picoliter-volume wells each containing a single bead and sequencing enzymes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Pyrosequencing uses luciferase to generate light for detection of the individual nucleotides added to the nascent DNA, and the combined data are used to generate sequence reads.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This technology provides intermediate read length and price per base compared to Sanger sequencing on one end and Solexa and SOLiD on the other.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Solexa, now part of Illumina, was founded by Shankar Balasubramanian and David Klenerman in 1998, and developed a sequencing method based on reversible dye-terminators technology, and engineered polymerases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The reversible terminated chemistry concept was invented by Bruno Canard and Simon Sarfati at the Pasteur Institute in Paris.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] It was developed internally at Solexa by those named on the relevant patents.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2004, Solexa acquired the company Manteia Predictive Medicine in order to gain a massively parallel sequencing technology invented in 1997 by Pascal Mayer and Laurent Farinelli.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] It is based on "DNA clusters" or "DNA colonies", which involves the clonal amplification of DNA on a surface.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The cluster technology was co-acquired with Lynx Therapeutics of California.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Solexa Ltd. later merged with Lynx to form Solexa Inc.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In this method, DNA molecules and primers are first attached on a slide or flow cell and amplified with polymerase so that local clonal DNA colonies, later coined "DNA clusters", are formed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] To determine the sequence, four types of reversible terminator bases (RT-bases) are added and non-incorporated nucleotides are washed away.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] A camera takes images of the fluorescently labeled nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Then the dye, along with the terminal 3' blocker, is chemically removed from the DNA, allowing for the next cycle to begin.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Unlike pyrosequencing, the DNA chains are extended one nucleotide at a time and image acquisition can be performed at a delayed moment, allowing for very large arrays of DNA colonies to be captured by sequential images taken from a single camera.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Decoupling the enzymatic reaction and the image capture allows for optimal throughput and theoretically unlimited sequencing capacity.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] 30x) per day per instrument (equipped with a single camera).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method is an upgraded modification to combinatorial probe anchor ligation technology (cPAL) described by Complete Genomics which has since become part of Chinese genomics company BGI in 2013.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The two companies have refined the technology to allow for longer read lengths, reaction time reductions and faster time to results.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In addition, data are now generated as contiguous full-length reads in the standard FASTQ file format and can be used as-is in most short-read-based bioinformatics analysis pipelines.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The two technologies that form the basis for this high-throughput sequencing technology are DNA nanoballs (DNB) and patterned arrays for nanoball attachment to a solid surface.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA nanoballs are simply formed by denaturing double stranded, adapter ligated libraries and ligating the forward strand only to a splint oligonucleotide to form a ssDNA circle.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Faithful copies of the circles containing the DNA insert are produced utilizing Rolling Circle Amplification that generates approximately 300–500 copies.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The long strand of ssDNA folds upon itself to produce a three-dimensional nanoball structure that is approximately 220 nm in diameter.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Making DNBs replaces the need to generate PCR copies of the library on the flow cell and as such can remove large proportions of duplicate reads, adapter-adapter ligations and PCR induced errors.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The patterned array of positively charged spots is fabricated through photolithography and etching techniques followed by chemical modification to generate a sequencing flow cell.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Each spot on the flow cell is approximately 250 nm in diameter, are separated by 700 nm (centre to centre) and allows easy attachment of a single negatively charged DNB to the flow cell and thus reducing under or over-clustering on the flow cell.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Sequencing is then performed by addition of an oligonucleotide probe that attaches in combination to specific sites within the DNB.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The probe acts as an anchor that then allows one of four single reversibly inactivated, labelled nucleotides to bind after flowing across the flow cell.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Unbound nucleotides are washed away before laser excitation of the attached labels then emit fluorescence and signal is captured by cameras that is converted to a digital output for base calling.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The attached base has its terminator and label chemically cleaved at completion of the cycle.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The cycle is repeated with another flow of free, labelled nucleotides across the flow cell to allow the next nucleotide to bind and have its signal captured.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This process is completed a number of times (usually 50 to 300 times) to determine the sequence of the inserted piece of DNA at a rate of approximately 40 million nucleotides per second as of 2018.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Applied Biosystems' (now a Life Technologies brand) SOLiD technology employs sequencing by ligation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Here, a pool of all possible oligonucleotides of a fixed length are labeled according to the sequenced position.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Oligonucleotides are annealed and ligated; the preferential ligation by DNA ligase for matching sequences results in a signal informative of the nucleotide at that position.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Each base in the template is sequenced twice, and the resulting data are decoded according to the 2 base encoding scheme used in this method.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Before sequencing, the DNA is amplified by emulsion PCR.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The resulting beads, each containing single copies of the same DNA molecule, are deposited on a glass slide.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The result is sequences of quantities and lengths comparable to Illumina sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This sequencing by ligation method has been reported to have some issue sequencing palindromic sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] (now owned by Life Technologies) developed a system based on using standard sequencing chemistry, but with a novel, semiconductor-based detection system.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method of sequencing is based on the detection of hydrogen ions that are released during the polymerisation of DNA, as opposed to the optical methods used in other sequencing systems.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] A microwell containing a template DNA strand to be sequenced is flooded with a single type of nucleotide.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] If the introduced nucleotide is complementary to the leading template nucleotide it is incorporated into the growing complementary strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This causes the release of a hydrogen ion that triggers a hypersensitive ion sensor, which indicates that a reaction has occurred.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] If homopolymer repeats are present in the template sequence, multiple nucleotides will be incorporated in a single cycle.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This leads to a corresponding number of released hydrogens and a proportionally higher electronic signal.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA nanoball sequencing is a type of high throughput sequencing technology used to determine the entire genomic sequence of an organism.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The company Complete Genomics uses this technology to sequence samples submitted by independent researchers.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The method uses rolling circle replication to amplify small fragments of genomic DNA into DNA nanoballs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Unchained sequencing by ligation is then used to determine the nucleotide sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This method of DNA sequencing allows large numbers of DNA nanoballs to be sequenced per run and at low reagent costs compared to other high-throughput sequencing platforms.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] However, only short sequences of DNA are determined from each DNA nanoball which makes mapping the short reads to a reference genome difficult.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Heliscope sequencing is a method of single-molecule sequencing developed by Helicos Biosciences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] It uses DNA fragments with added poly-A tail adapters which are attached to the flow cell surface.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The next steps involve extension-based sequencing with cyclic washes of the flow cell with fluorescently labeled nucleotides (one nucleotide type at a time, as with the Sanger method).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The reads are performed by the Heliscope sequencer.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] What made this technology especially novel was that it was the first of its class to sequence non-amplified DNA, thus preventing any read errors associated with amplification steps.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2009 a human genome was sequenced using the Heliscope, however in 2012 the company went bankrupt.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] There are two main microfluidic systems that are used to sequence DNA; droplet based microfluidics and digital microfluidics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Microfluidic devices solve many of the current limitations of current sequencing arrays.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Abate et al. studied the use of droplet-based microfluidic devices for DNA sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] These devices have the ability to form and process picoliter sized droplets at the rate of thousands per second.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The devices were created from polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) and used Forster resonance energy transfer, FRET assays to read the sequences of DNA encompassed in the droplets.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Each position on the array tested for a specific 15 base sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Fair et al. used digital microfluidic devices to study DNA pyrosequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Significant advantages include the portability of the device, reagent volume, speed of analysis, mass manufacturing abilities, and high throughput.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This study provided a proof of concept showing that digital devices can be used for pyrosequencing; the study included using synthesis, which involves the extension of the enzymes and addition of labeled nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] Boles et al. also studied pyrosequencing on digital microfluidic devices.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] They used an electro-wetting device to create, mix, and split droplets.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The sequencing uses a three-enzyme protocol and DNA templates anchored with magnetic beads.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The device was tested using two protocols and resulted in 100% accuracy based on raw pyrogram levels.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] The advantages of these digital microfluidic devices include size, cost, and achievable levels of functional integration.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing research, using microfluidics, also has the ability to be applied to the sequencing of RNA, using similar droplet microfluidic techniques, such as the method, inDrops.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p01] This shows that many of these DNA sequencing techniques will be able to be applied further and be used to understand more about genomes and transcriptomes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Third generation technologies aim to increase throughput and decrease the time to result and cost by eliminating the need for excessive reagents and harnessing the processivity of DNA polymerase.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Another approach uses measurements of the electrical tunnelling currents across single-strand DNA as it moves through a channel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Depending on its electronic structure, each base affects the tunnelling current differently, allowing differentiation between different bases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The use of tunnelling currents has the potential to sequence orders of magnitude faster than ionic current methods and the sequencing of several DNA oligomers and micro-RNA has already been achieved.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] This method of sequencing utilizes binding characteristics of a library of short single stranded DNA molecules (oligonucleotides), also called DNA probes, to reconstruct a target DNA sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Non-specific hybrids are removed by washing and the target DNA is eluted.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Hybrids are re-arranged such that the DNA sequence can be reconstructed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The benefit of this sequencing type is its ability to capture a large number of targets with a homogenous coverage.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] A large number of chemicals and starting DNA is usually required.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] However, with the advent of solution-based hybridization, much less equipment and chemicals are necessary.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Mass spectrometry may be used to determine DNA sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry, or MALDI-TOF MS, has specifically been investigated as an alternative method to gel electrophoresis for visualizing DNA fragments.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] With this method, DNA fragments generated by chain-termination sequencing reactions are compared by mass rather than by size.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The mass of each nucleotide is different from the others and this difference is detectable by mass spectrometry.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Single-nucleotide mutations in a fragment can be more easily detected with MS than by gel electrophoresis alone.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] MALDI-TOF MS can more easily detect differences between RNA fragments, so researchers may indirectly sequence DNA with MS-based methods by converting it to RNA first.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The higher resolution of DNA fragments permitted by MS-based methods is of special interest to researchers in forensic science, as they may wish to find single-nucleotide polymorphisms in human DNA samples to identify individuals.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] These samples may be highly degraded so forensic researchers often prefer mitochondrial DNA for its higher stability and applications for lineage studies.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] MS-based sequencing methods have been used to compare the sequences of human mitochondrial DNA from samples in a Federal Bureau of Investigation database and from bones found in mass graves of World War I soldiers.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Early chain-termination and TOF MS methods demonstrated read lengths of up to 100 base pairs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Researchers have been unable to exceed this average read size; like chain-termination sequencing alone, MS-based DNA sequencing may not be suitable for large *de novo* sequencing projects.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Even so, a 2010 study did use the short sequence reads and mass spectroscopy to compare single-nucleotide polymorphisms in pathogenic *Streptococcus* strains.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] In microfluidic Sanger sequencing the entire thermocycling amplification of DNA fragments as well as their separation by electrophoresis is done on a single glass wafer (approximately 10 cm in diameter) thus reducing the reagent usage as well as cost.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] In some instances researchers have shown that they can increase the throughput of conventional sequencing through the use of microchips.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Research will still need to be done in order to make this use of technology effective.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] This approach directly visualizes the sequence of DNA molecules using electron microscopy.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] This method is based on use of RNA polymerase (RNAP), which is attached to a polystyrene bead.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] One end of DNA to be sequenced is attached to another bead, with both beads being placed in optical traps.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] RNAP motion during transcription brings the beads in closer and their relative distance changes, which can then be recorded at a single nucleotide resolution.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The sequence is deduced based on the four readouts with lowered concentrations of each of the four nucleotide types, similarly to the Sanger method.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] A comparison is made between regions and sequence information is deduced by comparing the known sequence regions to the unknown sequence regions.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] A method has been developed to analyze full sets of protein interactions using a combination of 454 pyrosequencing and an *in vitro* virus mRNA display method.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Specifically, this method covalently links proteins of interest to the mRNAs encoding them, then detects the mRNA pieces using reverse transcription PCRs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The mRNA may then be amplified and sequenced.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The combined method was titled IVV-HiTSeq and can be performed under cell-free conditions, though its results may not be representative of *in vivo* conditions.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] While there are many different ways to sequence DNA, only a few dominate the market.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The success of any DNA sequencing protocol relies upon the DNA or RNA sample extraction and preparation from the biological material of interest.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] After DNA or RNA extraction, samples may require further preparation depending on the sequencing method.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] For Sanger sequencing, either cloning procedures or PCR are required prior to sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] In the case of next-generation sequencing methods, library preparation is required before processing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Assessing the quality and quantity of nucleic acids both after extraction and after library preparation identifies degraded, fragmented, and low-purity samples and yields high-quality sequencing data.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Each year the National Human Genome Research Institute, or NHGRI, promotes grants for new research and developments in genomics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] 2010 grants and 2011 candidates include continuing work in microfluidic, polony and base-heavy sequencing methodologies.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The sequencing technologies described here produce raw data that needs to be assembled into longer sequences such as complete genomes (sequence assembly).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] There are many computational challenges to achieve this, such as the evaluation of the raw sequence data which is done by programs and algorithms such as Phred and Phrap.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Other challenges have to deal with repetitive sequences that often prevent complete genome assemblies because they occur in many places of the genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] As a consequence, many sequences may not be assigned to particular chromosomes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] The production of raw sequence data is only the beginning of its detailed bioinformatical analysis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Yet new methods for sequencing and correcting sequencing errors were developed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Sometimes, the raw reads produced by the sequencer are correct and precise only in a fraction of their length.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Using the entire read may introduce artifacts in the downstream analyses like genome assembly, SNP calling, or gene expression estimation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Two classes of trimming programs have been introduced, based on the window-based or the running-sum classes of algorithms.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Human genetics have been included within the field of bioethics since the early 1970s and the growth in the use of DNA sequencing (particularly high-throughput sequencing) has introduced a number of ethical issues.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] One key issue is the ownership of an individual's DNA and the data produced when that DNA is sequenced.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Regarding the DNA molecule itself, the leading legal case on this topic, *Moore v.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Regents of the University of California* (1990) ruled that individuals have no property rights to discarded cells or any profits made using these cells (for instance, as a patented cell line).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] However, individuals have a right to informed consent regarding removal and use of cells.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Regarding the data produced through DNA sequencing, *Moore* gives the individual no rights to the information derived from their DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] As DNA sequencing becomes more widespread, the storage, security and sharing of genomic data has also become more important.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] For instance, one concern is that insurers may use an individual's genomic data to modify their quote, depending on the perceived future health of the individual based on their DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] In May 2008, the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) was signed in the United States, prohibiting discrimination on the basis of genetic information with respect to health insurance and employment.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] As of 2013, eleven states have laws that can be interpreted to prohibit "DNA theft".
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Ethical issues have also been raised by the increasing use of genetic variation screening, both in newborns, and in adults by companies such as 23andMe.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] It has been asserted that screening for genetic variations can be harmful, increasing anxiety in individuals who have been found to have an increased risk of disease.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] For example, in one case noted in *Time*, doctors screening an ill baby for genetic variants chose not to inform the parents of an unrelated variant linked to dementia due to the harm it would cause to the parents.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] However, a 2011 study in *The New England Journal of Medicine* has shown that individuals undergoing disease risk profiling did not show increased levels of anxiety.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/dna-sequencing-p02] Also, the development of Next Generation sequencing technologies such as Nanopore based sequencing has also raised further ethical concerns.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Nucleic acid molecules are separated by applying an electric field to move the negatively charged molecules through a gel matrix of agarose, polyacrylamide, or other substances.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Shorter molecules move faster and migrate farther than longer ones because shorter molecules flow more easily through the pores of the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Proteins are separated by the charge in agarose because the pores of the gel are too large to sieve proteins.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Gel electrophoresis can also be used for the separation of nanoparticles.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Gel electrophoresis uses a gel as an anticonvective medium or sieving medium during electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Gels suppress the thermal convection caused by the application of the electric field and can also serve to maintain the finished separation so that a post-electrophoresis stain can be applied.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Electrophoresis is a process that enables the sorting of molecules based on charge, size, or shape.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Using an electric field, molecules such as DNA can be made to move through a gel made of agarose or polyacrylamide.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The electric field consists of a negative charge at one end which pushes the molecules through the gel and a positive charge at the other end that pulls the molecules through the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The molecules being sorted are dispensed into a well in the gel material.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The gel is placed in an electrophoresis chamber, which is then connected to a power source.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] When the electric field is applied, the larger molecules move more slowly through the gel while the smaller molecules move faster.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The different sized molecules form distinct bands on the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The term "gel" in this instance refers to the matrix used to contain, then separate the target molecules.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] In most cases, the gel is a crosslinked polymer whose composition and porosity are chosen based on the specific weight and composition of the target to be analyzed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] When separating proteins or small nucleic acids (DNA, RNA, or oligonucleotides), the gel is usually composed of different concentrations of acrylamide and a cross-linker, producing different sized mesh networks of polyacrylamide.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] When separating larger nucleic acids (greater than a few hundred bases), the preferred matrix is purified agarose.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] In both cases, the gel forms a solid yet porous matrix.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Acrylamide, in contrast to polyacrylamide, is a neurotoxin and must be handled using appropriate safety precautions to avoid poisoning.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Agarose is composed of long unbranched chains of uncharged carbohydrates without cross-links, resulting in a gel with large pores allowing for the separation of macromolecules and macromolecular complexes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Electrophoresis refers to the electromotive force (EMF) that is used to move the molecules through the gel matrix.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] By placing the molecules in wells in the gel and applying an electric field, the molecules will move through the matrix at different rates, determined largely by their mass when the charge-to-mass ratio (Z) of all species is uniform.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] However, when charges are not uniform, the electrical field generated by the electrophoresis procedure will cause the molecules to migrate differentially according to charge.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Species that are net positively charged will migrate towards the cathode (which is negatively charged because this is an electrolytic rather than galvanic cell), whereas species that are net negatively charged will migrate towards the positively charged anode.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Mass remains a factor in the speed with which these non-uniformly charged molecules migrate through the matrix toward their respective electrodes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] If several samples have been loaded into adjacent wells in the gel, they will run parallel in individual lanes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Depending on the number of different molecules, each lane shows the separation of the components from the original mixture as one or more distinct bands, one band per component.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Incomplete separation of the components can lead to overlapping bands, or indistinguishable smears representing multiple unresolved components.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Bands in different lanes that end up at the same distance from the top contain molecules that passed through the gel at the same speed, which usually means they are approximately the same size.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] There are molecular weight size markers available that contain a mixture of molecules of known sizes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] If such a marker was run on one lane in the gel parallel to the unknown samples, the bands observed can be compared to those of the unknown to determine their size.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The distance a band travels is approximately inversely proportional to the logarithm of the size of the molecule.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] (Equivalently, the distance traveled is inversely proportional to the log of the samples's molecular weight).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] There are limits to electrophoretic techniques.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Since passing a current through a gel causes heating, gels may melt during electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Electrophoresis is performed in buffer solutions to reduce pH changes due to the electric field, which is important because the charge of DNA and RNA depends on pH, but running for too long can exhaust the buffering capacity of the solution.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] There are also limitations in determining the molecular weight by SDS-PAGE, especially when trying to find the MW of an unknown protein.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Certain biological variables are difficult or impossible to minimize and can affect electrophoretic migration.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Such factors include protein structure, post-translational modifications, and amino acid composition.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] For example, tropomyosin is an acidic protein that migrates abnormally on SDS-PAGE gels.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] This is because the acidic residues are repelled by the negatively charged SDS, leading to an inaccurate mass-to-charge ratio and migration.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Further, different preparations of genetic material may not migrate consistently with each other, for morphological or other reasons.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The types of gel most typically used are agarose and polyacrylamide gels.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Each type of gel is well-suited to different types and sizes of the analyte.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Polyacrylamide gels are usually used for proteins and have very high resolving power for small fragments of DNA (5-500 bp).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gels, on the other hand, have lower resolving power for DNA but a greater range of separation, and are therefore usually used for DNA fragments of 50–20,000 bp in size.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] (The resolution of over 6 Mb is possible with pulsed field gel electrophoresis (PFGE).) Polyacrylamide gels are run in a vertical configuration while agarose gels are typically run horizontally in a submarine mode.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] They also differ in their casting methodology, as agarose sets thermally, while polyacrylamide forms in a chemical polymerization reaction.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gels are made from the natural polysaccharide polymers extracted from seaweed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gels are easily cast and handled compared to other matrices because the gel setting is a physical rather than chemical change.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] After the experiment is finished, the resulting gel can be stored in a plastic bag in a refrigerator.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gels do not have a uniform pore size, but are optimal for electrophoresis of proteins that are larger than 200 kDa.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel electrophoresis can also be used for the separation of DNA fragments ranging from 50 base pair to several megabases (millions of bases), the largest of which require specialized apparatus.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The distance between DNA bands of different lengths is influenced by the percent agarose in the gel, with higher percentages requiring longer run times, sometimes days.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Instead high percentage agarose gels should be run with a pulsed field electrophoresis (PFE), or field inversion electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] "Most agarose gels are made with between 0.7% (good separation or resolution of large 5–10kb DNA fragments) and 2% (good resolution for small 0.2–1kb fragments) agarose dissolved in electrophoresis buffer.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Up to 3% can be used for separating very tiny fragments but a vertical polyacrylamide gel is more appropriate in this case.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Low percentage gels are very weak and may break when you try to lift them.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] High percentage gels are often brittle and do not set evenly.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (PAGE) is used for separating proteins ranging in size from 5 to 2,000 kDa due to the uniform pore size provided by the polyacrylamide gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Pore size is controlled by modulating the concentrations of acrylamide and bis-acrylamide powder and by the polymerization time used in creating a gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Care must be used when creating this type of gel, as acrylamide is a potent neurotoxin in its liquid and powdered forms.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Traditional DNA sequencing techniques such as Maxam-Gilbert or Sanger methods used polyacrylamide gels to separate DNA fragments differing by a single base-pair in length so the sequence could be read.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Most modern DNA separation methods now use agarose gels, except for particularly small DNA fragments.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] It is currently most often used in the field of immunology and protein analysis, often used to separate different proteins or isoforms of the same protein into separate bands.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] These can be transferred onto a nitrocellulose or PVDF membrane to be probed with antibodies and corresponding markers, such as in a western blot.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Stacking gel (5% T) is poured on top of the resolving gel and a gel comb (which forms the wells and defines the lanes where proteins, sample buffer, and ladders will be placed) is inserted.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The percentage chosen depends on the size of the protein that one wishes to identify or probe in the sample.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The smaller the known weight, the higher the percentage that should be used.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Changes in the buffer system of the gel can help to further resolve proteins of very small sizes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Partially hydrolysed potato starch makes for another non-toxic medium for protein electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The gels are slightly more opaque than acrylamide or agarose.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Non-denatured proteins can be separated according to charge and size.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] They are visualised using Napthal Black or Amido Black staining.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Typical starch gel concentrations are 5% to 10%.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Denaturing gels are run under conditions that disrupt the natural structure of the analyte, causing it to unfold into a linear chain.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Thus, the mobility of each macromolecule depends only on its linear length and its mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Thus, the secondary, tertiary, and quaternary levels of biomolecular structure are disrupted, leaving only the primary structure to be analyzed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Nucleic acids are often denatured by including urea in the buffer, while proteins are denatured using sodium dodecyl sulfate, usually as part of the SDS-PAGE process.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] For full denaturation of proteins, it is also necessary to reduce the covalent disulfide bonds that stabilize their tertiary and quaternary structure, a method called reducing PAGE.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Reducing conditions are usually maintained by the addition of beta-mercaptoethanol or dithiothreitol.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] For a general analysis of protein samples, reducing PAGE is the most common form of protein electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Denaturing conditions are necessary for proper estimation of molecular weight of RNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] RNA is able to form more intramolecular interactions than DNA which may result in change of its electrophoretic mobility.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Urea, DMSO and glyoxal are the most often used denaturing agents to disrupt RNA structure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Originally, highly toxic methylmercury hydroxide was often used in denaturing RNA electrophoresis, but it may be method of choice for some samples.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Denaturing gel electrophoresis is used in the DNA and RNA banding pattern-based methods temperature gradient gel electrophoresis (TGGE) and denaturing gradient gel electrophoresis (DGGE).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Native gels are run in non-denaturing conditions so that the analyte's natural structure is maintained.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] This allows the physical size of the folded or assembled complex to affect the mobility, allowing for analysis of all four levels of the biomolecular structure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] For biological samples, detergents are used only to the extent that they are necessary to lyse lipid membranes in the cell.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Complexes remain — for the most part — associated and folded as they would be in the cell.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] One downside, however, is that complexes may not separate cleanly or predictably, as it is difficult to predict how the molecule's shape and size will affect its mobility.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] These effects have been successfully addressed by preparative native PAGE.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Unlike denaturing methods, native gel electrophoresis does not use a charged denaturing agent.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The molecules being separated (usually proteins, peptides, or nucleic acids), therefore differ not only in molecular mass and intrinsic charge, but also the cross-sectional area, and thus, experience different electrophoretic forces dependent on the shape of the overall structure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] For proteins, since they remain in the native state, they may be visualized not only by general protein staining reagents but also by specific enzyme-linked staining.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] A specific experiment example of an application of native gel electrophoresis is to check for enzymatic activity to verify the presence of the enzyme in the sample during protein purification.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] For example, for the protein alkaline phosphatase, the staining solution is a mixture of 4-chloro-2-2 methylbenzenediazonium salt with 3-phospho-2-naphthoic acid-2'-4'-dimethyl aniline in Tris buffer.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] This stain is commercially sold as a kit for staining gels.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] If the protein is present, the mechanism of the reaction takes place in the following order: it starts with the de-phosphorylation of 3-phospho-2-naphthoic acid-2'-4'-dimethyl aniline by alkaline phosphatase (water is needed for the reaction).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The phosphate group is released and replaced by an alcohol group from water.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The electrophile 4- chloro-2-2 methylbenzenediazonium (*Fast Red TR Diazonium* salt) displaces the alcohol group forming the final product *Red Azo* dye.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] As its name implies, this is the final visible-red product of the reaction.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] In undergraduate academic experimentation of protein purification, the gel is usually run next to commercial purified samples to visualize the results and conclude whether or not purification was successful.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Native gel electrophoresis is typically used in proteomics and metallomics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] However, native PAGE is also used to scan genes (DNA) for unknown mutations as in single-strand conformation polymorphism.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Buffers in gel electrophoresis are used to provide ions that carry a current and to maintain the pH at a relatively constant value.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] These buffers have plenty of ions in them, which is necessary for the passage of electricity through them.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Something like distilled water or benzene contains few ions, which is not ideal for the use in electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] There are a number of buffers used for electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The most common being, for nucleic acids Tris/Acetate/EDTA (TAE), Tris/Borate/EDTA (TBE).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Many other buffers have been proposed, e.g. lithium borate (LB), (which is rarely used based on Pubmed citations), isoelectric histidine, pK matched Good's buffers, etc.; in most cases the purported rationale is lower current (less heat) matched ion mobilities, which leads to longer buffer life.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Borate is problematic as borate can polymerize or interact with cis diols such as those found in RNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] TAE has the lowest buffering capacity, but provides the best resolution for larger DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] This means a lower voltage and more time, but a better product.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] LB is relatively new and is ineffective in resolving fragments larger than 5 kbp; However, with its low conductivity, a much higher voltage could be used (up to 35 V/cm), which means a shorter analysis time for routine electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] As low as one base pair size difference could be resolved in 3% agarose gel with an extremely low conductivity medium (1 mM Lithium borate).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Most SDS-PAGE protein separations are performed using a "discontinuous" (or DISC) buffer system that significantly enhances the sharpness of the bands within the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] During electrophoresis in a discontinuous gel system, an ion gradient is formed in the early stage of electrophoresis that causes all of the proteins to focus on a single sharp band in a process called isotachophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Separation of the proteins by size is achieved in the lower, "resolving" region of the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The resolving gel typically has a much smaller pore size, which leads to a sieving effect that now determines the electrophoretic mobility of the proteins.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] After electrophoresis is complete, the molecules in the gel can be stained to make them visible.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] DNA may be visualized using ethidium bromide which, when intercalated into DNA, fluoresce under ultraviolet light, while protein may be visualised using silver stain or Coomassie brilliant blue dye.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Other methods may also be used to visualize the separation of the mixture's components on the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] If the molecules to be separated contain radioactivity, for example in a DNA sequencing gel, an autoradiogram can be recorded of the gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Photographs can be taken of gels, often using a gel doc system.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Gels are then commonly labelled for presentation using a number of tools, such as Adobe Illustrator, GIMP, ImageJ, Microsoft PowerPoint, and sciugo.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] After separation, an additional separation method may then be used, such as isoelectric focusing or SDS-PAGE.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The gel will then be physically cut, and the protein complexes extracted from each portion separately.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Each extract may then be analysed, such as by peptide mass fingerprinting or de novo peptide sequencing after in-gel digestion.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] This can provide a great deal of information about the identities of the proteins in a complex.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Gel electrophoresis is used in forensics, molecular biology, genetics, microbiology and biochemistry.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The results can be analyzed quantitatively by visualizing the gel with UV light and a gel imaging device.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The image is recorded with a computer-operated camera, and the intensity of the band or spot of interest is measured and compared against standard or markers loaded on the same gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The measurement and analysis are mostly done with specialized software.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Depending on the type of analysis being performed, other techniques are often implemented in conjunction with the results of gel electrophoresis, providing a wide range of field-specific applications.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] In the case of nucleic acids, the direction of migration, from negative to positive electrodes, is due to the naturally occurring negative charge carried by their sugar-phosphate backbone.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Double-stranded DNA fragments naturally behave as long rods, so their migration through the gel is relative to their size or, for cyclic fragments, their radius of gyration.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Circular DNA such as plasmids, however, may show multiple bands, the speed of migration may depend on whether it is relaxed or supercoiled.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Single-stranded DNA or RNA tends to fold up into molecules with complex shapes and migrate through the gel in a complicated manner based on their tertiary structure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Therefore, agents that disrupt the hydrogen bonds, such as sodium hydroxide or formamide, are used to denature the nucleic acids and cause them to behave as long rods again.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Gel electrophoresis of large DNA or RNA is usually done by agarose gel electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] See the "chain termination method" page for an example of a polyacrylamide DNA sequencing gel.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Characterization through ligand interaction of nucleic acids or fragments may be performed by mobility shift affinity electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Electrophoresis of RNA samples can be used to check for genomic DNA contamination and also for RNA degradation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] RNA from eukaryotic organisms shows distinct bands of 28s and 18s rRNA, the 28s band being approximately twice as intense as the 18s band.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Degraded RNA has less sharply defined bands, has a smeared appearance, and the intensity ratio is less than 2:1.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Proteins, unlike nucleic acids, can have varying charges and complex shapes, therefore they may not migrate into the polyacrylamide gel at similar rates, or all when placing a negative to positive EMF on the sample.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Proteins, therefore, are usually denatured in the presence of a detergent such as sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) that coats the proteins with a negative charge.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Generally, the amount of SDS bound is relative to the size of the protein (usually 1.4g SDS per gram of protein), so that the resulting denatured proteins have an overall negative charge, and all the proteins have a similar charge-to-mass ratio.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Since denatured proteins act like long rods instead of having a complex tertiary shape, the rate at which the resulting SDS coated proteins migrate in the gel is relative only to their size and not their charge or shape.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Proteins are usually analyzed by sodium dodecyl sulfate polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE), by blue native or clear native PAGE, by preparative native PAGE, or by 2-D electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Characterization through ligand interaction may be performed by electroblotting or by affinity electrophoresis in agarose or by capillary electrophoresis as for estimation of binding constants and determination of structural features like glycan content through lectin binding.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] A novel application for gel electrophoresis is the separation or characterization of metal or metal oxide nanoparticles (e.g.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Au, Ag, ZnO, SiO2) regarding the size, shape, or surface chemistry of the nanoparticles.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] The scope is to obtain a more homogeneous sample (e.g. narrower particle size distribution), which then can be used in further products/processes (e.g. self-assembly processes).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] A 1959 book on electrophoresis by Milan Bier cites references from the 1800s.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] However, Oliver Smithies made significant contributions.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/gel-electrophoresis] Bier states: "The method of Smithies ... is finding wide application because of its unique separatory power." Taken in context, Bier clearly implies that Smithies' method is an improvement.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] Maxam–Gilbert sequencing was the first widely adopted method for DNA sequencing, and, along with the Sanger dideoxy method, represents the first generation of DNA sequencing methods.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] Maxam–Gilbert sequencing is no longer in widespread use, having been supplanted by next-generation sequencing methods.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] However, with the improvement of the chain-termination method (see below), Maxam–Gilbert sequencing has fallen out of favour due to its technical complexity prohibiting its use in standard molecular biology kits, extensive use of hazardous chemicals, and difficulties with scale-up.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] Allan Maxam and Walter Gilbert’s 1977 paper “A new method for sequencing DNA” was honored by a Citation for Chemical Breakthrough Award from the Division of History of Chemistry of the American Chemical Society for 2017.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] It was presented to the Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology, Harvard University.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] Maxam–Gilbert sequencing requires radioactive labeling at one 5′ end of the DNA fragment to be sequenced (typically by a kinase reaction using gamma-32P ATP) and purification of the DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] Chemical treatment generates breaks at a small proportion of one or two of the four nucleotide bases in each of four reactions (G, A+G, C, C+T).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] For example, the purines (A+G) are depurinated using formic acid, the guanines (and to some extent the adenines) are methylated by dimethyl sulfate, and the pyrimidines (C+T) are hydrolysed using hydrazine.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] The addition of salt (sodium chloride) to the hydrazine reaction inhibits the reaction of thymine for the C-only reaction.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] The modified DNAs may then be cleaved by hot piperidine; (CH2)5NH at the position of the modified base.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] To visualize the fragments, the gel is exposed to X-ray film for autoradiography, yielding a series of dark bands each showing the location of identical radiolabeled DNA molecules.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] From presence and absence of certain fragments the sequence may be inferred.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] This method led to the Methylation Interference Assay, used to map DNA-binding sites for DNA-binding proteins.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/maxam-gilbert-sequencing] An automated Maxam–Gilbert sequencing protocol was developed in 1994.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] A **nucleic acid sequence** is a succession of bases within the nucleotides forming alleles within a DNA (using GACT) or RNA (GACU) molecule.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] This succession is denoted by a series of a set of five different letters that indicate the order of the nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] By convention, sequences are usually presented from the 5' end to the 3' end.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] For DNA, with its double helix, there are two possible directions for the notated sequence; of these two, the sense strand is used.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Because nucleic acids are normally linear (unbranched) polymers, specifying the sequence is equivalent to defining the covalent structure of the entire molecule.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] For this reason, the nucleic acid sequence is also termed the primary structure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The sequence represents **genetic information**.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Biological deoxyribonucleic acid represents the information which directs the functions of an organism.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Nucleic acids also have a secondary structure and tertiary structure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Primary structure is sometimes mistakenly referred to as "primary sequence".
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] However there is no parallel concept of secondary or tertiary sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Nucleic acids consist of a chain of linked units called nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Each nucleotide consists of three subunits: a phosphate group and a sugar (ribose in the case of RNA, deoxyribose in DNA) make up the backbone of the nucleic acid strand, and attached to the sugar is one of a set of nucleobases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The nucleobases are important in base pairing of strands to form higher-level secondary and tertiary structures such as the famed double helix.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The possible letters are *A*, *C*, *G*, and *T*, representing the four nucleotide bases of a DNA strand – adenine, cytosine, guanine, thymine – covalently linked to a phosphodiester backbone.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In the typical case, the sequences are printed abutting one another without gaps, as in the sequence AAAGTCTGAC, read left to right in the 5' to 3' direction.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] With regards to transcription, a sequence is on the coding strand if it has the same order as the transcribed RNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] One sequence can be complementary to another sequence, meaning that they have the base on each position in the complementary (i.e., A to T, C to G) and in the reverse order.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] For example, the complementary sequence to TTAC is GTAA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] If one strand of the double-stranded DNA is considered the sense strand, then the other strand, considered the antisense strand, will have the complementary sequence to the sense strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] While A, T, C, and G represent a particular nucleotide at a position, there are also letters that represent ambiguity which are used when more than one kind of nucleotide could occur at that position.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] For example, **W** means that either an adenine or a thymine could occur in that position without impairing the sequence's functionality.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] These symbols are also valid for RNA, except with U (uracil) replacing T (thymine).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Apart from adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G), thymine (T) and uracil (U), DNA and RNA also contain bases that have been modified after the nucleic acid chain has been formed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In DNA, the most common modified base is 5-methylcytidine (m5C).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In RNA, there are many modified bases, including pseudouridine (Ψ), dihydrouridine (D), inosine (I), ribothymidine (rT) and 7-methylguanosine (m7G).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Hypoxanthine and xanthine are two of the many bases created through mutagen presence, both of them through deamination (replacement of the amine-group with a carbonyl-group).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Hypoxanthine is produced from adenine, and xanthine is produced from guanine.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Similarly, deamination of cytosine results in uracil.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Given the two 10-nucleotide sequences, line them up and compare the differences between them.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Calculate the percent difference by taking the number of differences between the DNA bases divided by the total number of nucleotides.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In this case there are three differences in the 10 nucleotide sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In biological systems, nucleic acids contain information which is used by a living cell to construct specific proteins.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The sequence of nucleobases on a nucleic acid strand is translated by cell machinery into a sequence of amino acids making up a protein strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Each group of three bases, called a codon, corresponds to a single amino acid, and there is a specific genetic code by which each possible combination of three bases corresponds to a specific amino acid.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The central dogma of molecular biology outlines the mechanism by which proteins are constructed using information contained in nucleic acids.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] DNA is transcribed into mRNA molecules, which travel to the ribosome where the mRNA is used as a template for the construction of the protein strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Since nucleic acids can bind to molecules with complementary sequences, there is a distinction between "sense" sequences which code for proteins, and the complementary "antisense" sequence, which is by itself nonfunctional, but can bind to the sense strand.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] DNA sequencing is the process of determining the nucleotide sequence of a given DNA fragment.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The sequence of the DNA of a living thing encodes the necessary information for that living thing to survive and reproduce.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Therefore, determining the sequence is useful in fundamental research into why and how organisms live, as well as in applied subjects.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Because of the importance of DNA to living things, knowledge of a DNA sequence may be useful in practically any biological research.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] For example, in medicine it can be used to identify, diagnose and potentially develop treatments for genetic diseases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Similarly, research into pathogens may lead to treatments for contagious diseases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Biotechnology is a burgeoning discipline, with the potential for many useful products and services.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Instead, it is copied to a DNA by reverse transcriptase, and this DNA is then sequenced.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Current sequencing methods rely on the discriminatory ability of DNA polymerases, and therefore can only distinguish four bases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] An inosine (created from adenosine during RNA editing) is read as a G, and 5-methyl-cytosine (created from cytosine by DNA methylation) is read as a C.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] With current technology, it is difficult to sequence small amounts of DNA, as the signal is too weak to measure.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] This is overcome by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) amplification.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Once a nucleic acid sequence has been obtained from an organism, it is stored *in silico* in digital format.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Digital genetic sequences may be stored in sequence databases, be analyzed (see *Sequence analysis* below), be digitally altered and be used as templates for creating new actual DNA using artificial gene synthesis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Digital genetic sequences may be analyzed using the tools of bioinformatics to attempt to determine its function.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The DNA in an organism's genome can be analyzed to diagnose vulnerabilities to inherited diseases, and can also be used to determine a child's paternity (genetic father) or a person's ancestry.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Normally, every person carries two variations of every gene, one inherited from their mother, the other inherited from their father.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The human genome is believed to contain around 20,000–25,000 genes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In addition to studying chromosomes to the level of individual genes, genetic testing in a broader sense includes biochemical tests for the possible presence of genetic diseases, or mutant forms of genes associated with increased risk of developing genetic disorders.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Genetic testing identifies changes in chromosomes, genes, or proteins.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Usually, testing is used to find changes that are associated with inherited disorders.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The results of a genetic test can confirm or rule out a suspected genetic condition or help determine a person's chance of developing or passing on a genetic disorder.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Several hundred genetic tests are currently in use, and more are being developed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In bioinformatics, a sequence alignment is a way of arranging the sequences of DNA, RNA, or protein to identify regions of similarity that may be due to functional, structural, or evolutionary relationships between the sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] If two sequences in an alignment share a common ancestor, mismatches can be interpreted as point mutations and gaps as insertion or deletion mutations (indels) introduced in one or both lineages in the time since they diverged from one another.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In sequence alignments of proteins, the degree of similarity between amino acids occupying a particular position in the sequence can be interpreted as a rough measure of how conserved a particular region or sequence motif is among lineages.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The absence of substitutions, or the presence of only very conservative substitutions (that is, the substitution of amino acids whose side chains have similar biochemical properties) in a particular region of the sequence, suggest that this region has structural or functional importance.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Although DNA and RNA nucleotide bases are more similar to each other than are amino acids, the conservation of base pairs can indicate a similar functional or structural role.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Computational phylogenetics makes extensive use of sequence alignments in the construction and interpretation of phylogenetic trees, which are used to classify the evolutionary relationships between homologous genes represented in the genomes of divergent species.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The degree to which sequences in a query set differ is qualitatively related to the sequences' evolutionary distance from one another.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Roughly speaking, high sequence identity suggests that the sequences in question have a comparatively young most recent common ancestor, while low identity suggests that the divergence is more ancient.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Therefore, it does not account for possible differences among organisms or species in the rates of DNA repair or the possible functional conservation of specific regions in a sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Frequently the primary structure encodes motifs that are of functional importance.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] Some examples of sequence motifs are: the C/D and H/ACA boxes of snoRNAs, Sm binding site found in spliceosomal RNAs such as U1, U2, U4, U5, U6, U12 and U3, the Shine-Dalgarno sequence, the Kozak consensus sequence and the RNA polymerase III terminator.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] In bioinformatics, a sequence entropy, also known as sequence complexity or information profile, is a numerical sequence providing a quantitative measure of the local complexity of a DNA sequence, independently of the direction of processing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/nucleic-acid-sequence] The manipulations of the information profiles enable the analysis of the sequences using alignment-free techniques, such as for example in motif and rearrangements detection.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Recently, higher volume Sanger sequencing has been replaced by next generation sequencing methods, especially for large-scale, automated genome analyses.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] However, the Sanger method remains in wide use for smaller-scale projects and for validation of deep sequencing results.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] It still has the advantage over short-read sequencing technologies (like Illumina) in that it can produce DNA sequence reads of > 500 nucleotides and maintains a very low error rate with accuracies around 99.99%.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The classical chain-termination method requires a single-stranded DNA template, a DNA primer, a DNA polymerase, normal deoxynucleotide triphosphates (dNTPs), and modified di-deoxynucleotide triphosphates (ddNTPs), the latter of which terminate DNA strand elongation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] These chain-terminating nucleotides lack a 3'-OH group required for the formation of a phosphodiester bond between two nucleotides, causing DNA polymerase to cease extension of DNA when a modified ddNTP is incorporated.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The ddNTPs may be radioactively or fluorescently labelled for detection in automated sequencing machines.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The DNA sample is multiplied into four separate sequencing reactions, containing all four of the standard deoxynucleotides (dATP, dGTP, dCTP and dTTP) and the DNA polymerase.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] To each reaction is added only one of the four dideoxynucleotides (ddATP, ddGTP, ddCTP, or ddTTP), while the other added nucleotides are ordinary ones.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The deoxynucleotide concentration should be about 100-fold higher than that of the corresponding dideoxynucleotide (e.g.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] 0.5mM dTTP : 0.005mM ddTTP) to allow enough fragments to be produced while still transcribing the complete sequence (but the concentration of ddNTP also depends on the desired length of sequence).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] In other words, four separate reactions are needed in this process to test all four ddNTPs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Following rounds of template DNA extension from the bound primer, the resulting DNA fragments are heat denatured and separated by size using gel electrophoresis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] In the original publication of 1977, the formation of base-paired loops of ssDNA was a cause of serious difficulty in resolving bands at some locations.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] This is frequently performed using a denaturing polyacrylamide-urea gel with each of the four reactions run in one of four individual lanes (lanes A, T, G, C).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The DNA bands may then be visualized by autoradiography or UV light, and the DNA sequence can be directly read off the X-ray film or gel image.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] In the image on the right, X-ray film was exposed to the gel, and the dark bands correspond to DNA fragments of different lengths.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] A dark band in a lane indicates a DNA fragment that is the result of chain termination after incorporation of a dideoxynucleotide (ddATP, ddGTP, ddCTP, or ddTTP).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The relative positions of the different bands among the four lanes, from bottom to top, are then used to read the DNA sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Technical variations of chain-termination sequencing include tagging with nucleotides containing radioactive phosphorus for radiolabelling, or using a primer labeled at the 5' end with a fluorescent dye.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Dye-primer sequencing facilitates reading in an optical system for slow and harder analysis and automation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The later development by Leroy Hood and coworkers of fluorescently labeled ddNTPs and primers set the stage for automated, high-throughput DNA sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Chain-termination methods have greatly simplified DNA sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] For example, chain-termination-based kits are commercially available that contain the reagents needed for sequencing, pre-aliquoted and ready to use.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Limitations include non-specific binding of the primer to the DNA, affecting accurate read-out of the DNA sequence, and DNA secondary structures affecting the fidelity of the sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Owing to its greater expediency and speed, dye-terminator sequencing is now the mainstay in automated sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] This problem has been addressed with the use of modified DNA polymerase enzyme systems and dyes that minimize incorporation variability, as well as methods for eliminating "dye blobs".
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The dye-terminator sequencing method, along with automated high-throughput DNA sequence analyzers, was used for the vast majority of sequencing projects until the introduction of next generation sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Automated DNA-sequencing instruments (DNA sequencers) can sequence up to 384 DNA samples in a single batch.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Batch runs may occur up to 24 times a day.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] DNA sequencers separate strands by size (or length) using capillary electrophoresis, they detect and record dye fluorescence, and output data as fluorescent peak trace chromatograms.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Sequencing reactions (thermocycling and labelling), cleanup and re-suspension of samples in a buffer solution are performed separately, before loading samples onto the sequencer.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] A number of commercial and non-commercial software packages can trim low-quality DNA traces automatically.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] These programs score the quality of each peak and remove low-quality base peaks (which are generally located at the ends of the sequence).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The accuracy of such algorithms is inferior to visual examination by a human operator, but is adequate for automated processing of large sequence data sets.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The field of public health plays many roles to support patient diagnostics as well as environmental surveillance of potential toxic substances and circulating biological pathogens.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Public health laboratories (PHL) and other laboratories around the world have played a pivotal role in providing rapid sequencing data for the surveillance of the virus SARS-CoV-2, causative agent for COVID-19, during the pandemic that was declared a public health emergency on January 30, 2020.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Laboratories were tasked with the rapid implementation of sequencing methods and asked to provide accurate data to assist in the decision-making models for the development of policies to mitigate spread of the virus.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Many laboratories resorted to next generation sequencing methodologies while others supported efforts with Sanger sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The sequencing efforts of SARS-CoV-2 are many, while most laboratories implemented whole genome sequencing of the virus, others have opted to sequence very specific genes of the virus such as the S-gene, encoding the information needed to produce the spike protein.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The high mutation rate of SARS-CoV-2 leads to genetic differences within the S-gene and these differences have played a role in the infectivity of the virus.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Sanger sequencing of the S-gene provides a quick, accurate, and more affordable method to retrieving the genetic code.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Laboratories in lower income countries may not have the capabilities to implement expensive applications such as next generation sequencing, so Sanger methods may prevail in supporting the generation of sequencing data for surveillance of variants.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Sanger sequencing is also the "gold standard" for norovirus surveillance methods for the Center for Disease Control and Prevention's (CDC) CaliciNet network.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] CalciNet is an outbreak surveillance network that was established in March 2009.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The goal of the network is to collect sequencing data of circulating noroviruses in the United States and activate downstream action to determine the source of infection to mitigate the spread of the virus.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The CalciNet network has identified many infections as foodborne illnesses.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] This data can then be published and used to develop recommendations for future action to prevent tainting food.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The methods employed for detection of norovirus involve targeted amplification of specific areas of the genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The amplicons are then sequenced using dye-terminating Sanger sequencing and the chromatograms and sequences generated are analyzed with a software package developed in BioNumerics.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Sequences are tracked and strain relatedness is studied to infer epidemiological relevance.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Common challenges of DNA sequencing with the Sanger method include poor quality in the first 15–40 bases of the sequence due to primer binding and deteriorating quality of sequencing traces after 700–900 bases.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Base calling software such as Phred typically provides an estimate of quality to aid in trimming of low-quality regions of sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] In cases where DNA fragments are cloned before sequencing, the resulting sequence may contain parts of the cloning vector.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] In contrast, PCR-based cloning and next-generation sequencing technologies based on pyrosequencing often avoid using cloning vectors.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Recently, one-step Sanger sequencing (combined amplification and sequencing) methods such as Ampliseq and SeqSharp have been developed that allow rapid sequencing of target genes without cloning or prior amplification.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Current methods can directly sequence only relatively short (300–1000 nucleotides long) DNA fragments in a single reaction.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The main obstacle to sequencing DNA fragments above this size limit is insufficient power of separation for resolving large DNA fragments that differ in length by only one nucleotide.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Microfluidic Sanger sequencing is a lab-on-a-chip application for DNA sequencing, in which the Sanger sequencing steps (thermal cycling, sample purification, and capillary electrophoresis) are integrated on a wafer-scale chip using nanoliter-scale sample volumes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] In its modern inception, high-throughput genome sequencing involves fragmenting the genome into small single-stranded pieces, followed by amplification of the fragments by polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Amplified base ladders are then separated by capillary array electrophoresis (CAE) with automated, *in situ* "finish-line" detection of the fluorescently labeled ssDNA fragments, which provides an ordered sequence of the fragments.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] These sequence reads are then computer assembled into overlapping or contiguous sequences (termed "contigs") which resemble the full genomic sequence once fully assembled.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Sanger methods achieve maximum read lengths of approximately 800 bp (typically 500–600 bp with non-enriched DNA).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The longer read lengths in Sanger methods display significant advantages over other sequencing methods especially in terms of sequencing repetitive regions of the genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] A challenge of short-read sequence data is particularly an issue in sequencing new genomes *(de novo)* and in sequencing highly rearranged genome segments, typically those seen of cancer genomes or in regions of chromosomes that exhibit structural variation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Other useful applications of DNA sequencing include single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) detection, single-strand conformation polymorphism (SSCP) heteroduplex analysis, and short tandem repeat (STR) analysis.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Resolving DNA fragments according to differences in size and/or conformation is the most critical step in studying these features of the genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The sequencing chip has a four-layer construction, consisting of three 100-mm-diameter glass wafers (on which device elements are microfabricated) and a polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) membrane.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Reaction chambers and capillary electrophoresis channels are etched between the top two glass wafers, which are thermally bonded.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Three-dimensional channel interconnections and microvalves are formed by the PDMS and bottom manifold glass wafer.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The device consists of three functional units, each corresponding to the Sanger sequencing steps.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The thermal cycling (TC) unit is a 250-nanoliter reaction chamber with integrated resistive temperature detector, microvalves, and a surface heater.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The movement of reagent between the top all-glass layer and the lower glass-PDMS layer occurs through 500-μm-diameter via-holes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] After thermal-cycling, the reaction mixture undergoes purification in the capture/purification chamber, and then is injected into the capillary electrophoresis (CE) chamber.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The CE unit consists of a 30-cm capillary which is folded into a compact switchback pattern via 65-μm-wide turns.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] applied between capture outlet and inlet ports.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The capture gel through which the sample is driven, consists of 40 μM of oligonucleotide (complementary to the primers) covalently bound to a polyacrylamide matrix.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Extension fragments are immobilised by the gel matrix, and excess primer, template, free nucleotides, and salts are eluted through the capture waste port.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Extension fragments are injected into the CE chamber where they are electrophoresed through a 125-167-V/cm field.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The Apollo 100 platform (Microchip Biotechnologies Inc., Dublin, California) integrates the first two Sanger sequencing steps (thermal cycling and purification) in a fully automated system.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The manufacturer claims that samples are ready for capillary electrophoresis within three hours of the sample and reagents being loaded into the system.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The Apollo 100 platform requires sub-microliter volumes of reagents.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] The ultimate goal of high-throughput sequencing is to develop systems that are low-cost, and extremely efficient at obtaining extended (longer) read lengths.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Longer read lengths of each single electrophoretic separation, substantially reduces the cost associated with de novo DNA sequencing and the number of templates needed to sequence DNA contigs at a given redundancy.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/sanger-sequencing] Microfluidics may allow for faster, cheaper and easier sequence assembly.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In genetics, **shotgun sequencing** is a method used for sequencing random DNA strands.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] It is named by analogy with the rapidly expanding, quasi-random shot grouping of a shotgun.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The chain-termination method of DNA sequencing ("Sanger sequencing") can only be used for short DNA strands of 100 to 1000 base pairs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Due to this size limit, longer sequences are subdivided into smaller fragments that can be sequenced separately, and these sequences are assembled to give the overall sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In shotgun sequencing, DNA is broken up randomly into numerous small segments, which are sequenced using the chain termination method to obtain *reads*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Multiple overlapping reads for the target DNA are obtained by performing several rounds of this fragmentation and sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Computer programs then use the overlapping ends of different reads to assemble them into a continuous sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Shotgun sequencing was one of the precursor technologies that was responsible for enabling whole genome sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In this extremely simplified example, none of the reads cover the full length of the original sequence, but the four reads can be assembled into the original sequence using the overlap of their ends to align and order them.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In reality, this process uses enormous amounts of information that are rife with ambiguities and sequencing errors.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Assembly of complex genomes is additionally complicated by the great abundance of repetitive sequences, meaning similar short reads could come from completely different parts of the sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Many overlapping reads for each segment of the original DNA are necessary to overcome these difficulties and accurately assemble the sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] For example, to complete the Human Genome Project, most of the human genome was sequenced at 12X or greater *coverage*; that is, each base in the final sequence was present on average in 12 different reads.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Even so, current methods have failed to isolate or assemble reliable sequence for approximately 1% of the (euchromatic) human genome, as of 2004.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Whole genome shotgun sequencing for small (4000- to 7000-base-pair) genomes was first suggested in 1979.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The first genome sequenced by shotgun sequencing was that of cauliflower mosaic virus, published in 1981.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Broader application benefited from pairwise end sequencing, known colloquially as *double-barrel shotgun sequencing*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] As sequencing projects began to take on longer and more complicated DNA sequences, multiple groups began to realize that useful information could be obtained by sequencing both ends of a fragment of DNA.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] To apply the strategy, a high-molecular-weight DNA strand is sheared into random fragments, size-selected (usually 2, 10, 50, and 150 kb), and cloned into an appropriate vector.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The clones are then sequenced from both ends using the chain termination method yielding two short sequences.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Each sequence is called an *end-read* or *read 1 and read 2* and two reads from the same clone are referred to as *mate pairs*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Since the chain termination method usually can only produce reads between 500 and 1000 bases long, in all but the smallest clones, mate pairs will rarely overlap.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The original sequence is reconstructed from the reads using sequence assembly software.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] First, overlapping reads are collected into longer composite sequences known as *contigs*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Contigs can be linked together into *scaffolds* by following connections between mate pairs.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The distance between contigs can be inferred from the mate pair positions if the average fragment length of the library is known and has a narrow window of deviation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Depending on the size of the gap between contigs, different techniques can be used to find the sequence in the gaps.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] If the gap is small (5-20kb) then the use of polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to amplify the region is required, followed by sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] If the gap is large (>20kb) then the large fragment is cloned in special vectors such as bacterial artificial chromosomes (BAC) followed by sequencing of the vector.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Proponents of this approach argue that it is possible to sequence the whole genome at once using large arrays of sequencers, which makes the whole process much more efficient than more traditional approaches.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Detractors argue that although the technique quickly sequences large regions of DNA, its ability to correctly link these regions is suspect, particularly for eukaryotic genomes with repeating regions.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] As sequence assembly programs become more sophisticated and computing power becomes cheaper, it may be possible to overcome this limitation.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Coverage (read depth or depth) is the average number of reads representing a given nucleotide in the reconstructed sequence.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] It can be calculated from the length of the original genome (*G*), the number of reads(*N*), and the average read length(*L*) as $N\times L/G$ .
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] For example, a hypothetical genome with 2,000 base pairs reconstructed from 8 reads with an average length of 500 nucleotides will have 2x redundancy.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] This parameter also enables one to estimate other quantities, such as the percentage of the genome covered by reads (sometimes also called coverage).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] A high coverage in shotgun sequencing is desired because it can overcome errors in base calling and assembly.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The subject of DNA sequencing theory addresses the relationships of such quantities.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Sometimes a distinction is made between *sequence coverage* and *physical coverage*.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Sequence coverage is the average number of times a base is read (as described above).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Physical coverage is the average number of times a base is read or spanned by mate paired reads.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Historically, full-genome shotgun sequencing was believed to be limited by both the sheer size of large genomes and by the complexity added by the high percentage of repetitive DNA (greater than 50% for the human genome) present in large genomes.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] It was not widely accepted that a full-genome shotgun sequence of a large genome would provide reliable data.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] For these reasons, other strategies that lowered the computational load of sequence assembly had to be utilized before shotgun sequencing was performed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In hierarchical sequencing, also known as top-down sequencing, a low-resolution physical map of the genome is made prior to actual sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] From this map, a minimal number of fragments that cover the entire chromosome are selected for sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In this way, the minimum amount of high-throughput sequencing and assembly is required.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The amplified genome is first sheared into larger pieces (50-200kb) and cloned into a bacterial host using BACs or P1-derived artificial chromosomes (PAC).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Because multiple genome copies have been sheared at random, the fragments contained in these clones have different ends, and with enough coverage (see section above) finding the smallest possible **scaffold** of BAC contigs that covers the entire genome is theoretically possible.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] This scaffold is called the **minimum tiling path**.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Once a tiling path has been found, the BACs that form this path are sheared at random into smaller fragments and can be sequenced using the shotgun method on a smaller scale.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Although the full sequences of the BAC contigs is not known, their orientations relative to one another are known.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] There are several methods for deducing this order and selecting the BACs that make up a tiling path.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The general strategy involves identifying the positions of the clones relative to one another and then selecting the fewest clones required to form a contiguous scaffold that covers the entire area of interest.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The order of the clones is deduced by determining the way in which they overlap.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Overlapping clones can be identified in several ways.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] A small radioactively or chemically labeled probe containing a sequence-tagged site (STS) can be hybridized onto a microarray upon which the clones are printed.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] In this way, all the clones that contain a particular sequence in the genome are identified.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The end of one of these clones can then be sequenced to yield a new probe and the process repeated in a method called chromosome walking.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Alternatively, the BAC library can be restriction-digested.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Two clones that have several fragment sizes in common are inferred to overlap because they contain multiple similarly spaced restriction sites in common.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] This method of genomic mapping is called restriction or BAC fingerprinting because it identifies a set of restriction sites contained in each clone.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Once the overlap between the clones has been found and their order relative to the genome known, a scaffold of a minimal subset of these contigs that covers the entire genome is shotgun-sequenced.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Because it involves first creating a low-resolution map of the genome, hierarchical shotgun sequencing is slower than whole-genome shotgun sequencing, but relies less heavily on computer algorithms than whole-genome shotgun sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The process of extensive BAC library creation and tiling path selection, however, make hierarchical shotgun sequencing slow and labor-intensive.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Now that the technology is available and the reliability of the data demonstrated, the speed and cost efficiency of whole-genome shotgun sequencing has made it the primary method for genome sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The classical shotgun sequencing was based on the Sanger sequencing method: this was the most advanced technique for sequencing genomes from about 1995–2005.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The shotgun strategy is still applied today, however using other sequencing technologies, such as short-read sequencing and long-read sequencing.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Short-read or "next-gen" sequencing produces shorter reads (anywhere from 25–500bp) but many hundreds of thousands or millions of reads in a relatively short time (on the order of a day).
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] This results in high coverage, but the assembly process is much more computationally intensive.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] These technologies are vastly superior to Sanger sequencing due to the high volume of data and the relatively short time it takes to sequence a whole genome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Having reads of 400-500 base pairs length is sufficient to determine the species or strain of the organism where the DNA comes from, provided its genome is already known, by using for example a *k*-mer based taxonomic classifier software.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] With millions of reads from next generation sequencing of an environmental sample, it is possible to get a complete overview of any complex microbiome with thousands of species, like the gut flora.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] Advantages over 16S rRNA amplicon sequencing are: not being limited to bacteria; strain-level classification where amplicon sequencing only gets the genus; and the possibility to extract whole genes and specify their function as part of the metagenome.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] The sensitivity of metagenomic sequencing makes it an attractive choice for clinical use.
[src:dna-sequencing-methods/shotgun-sequencing] It however emphasizes the problem of contamination of the sample or the sequencing pipeline.
